-- 
Asian Stocks Rise to Highest Since March 11 on Japanese Factory Restarts

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s   a n d   T o s h i r o   H a s e g a w a
-- 
2011-03-30T10:28:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-30/asia-stocks-rise-as-japanese-companies-resume-production-nissan-bhp-gain.html
Asian stocks rose, driving the
regional benchmark index toward its highest level since March 11,
as Japanese companies began resuming production and those in
 China  reported earnings that beat estimates.  Hitachi Ltd. (6501) , the Japanese maker of products from home
appliances to nuclear reactors, jumped 8.7 percent in  Tokyo 
after the Nikkei newspaper reported its main factory in  Japan 
will resume full production next month. Li & Fung Ltd., the
biggest supplier to Wal-Mart Stores Inc., surged 5 percent in
 Hong Kong  ahead of U.S. employment data.  Cheung Kong Holdings
Ltd. (1) , Hong Kong’s No. 2 developer, advanced 4 percent after
posting full-year earnings that exceeded analyst estimates.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index gained 1.3 percent to 134.80
as of 7:27 p.m. in Tokyo, heading for its highest close since
March 11, when Japan was hit by its strongest earthquake on
record. Five stocks advanced for each that declined in the
measure.  “Even as Japan faces the unexpected effects of the huge
earthquake, the U.S. economic recovery is looking clearer,”
said  Hiroichi Nishi , an equities manager in Tokyo at Nikko
Cordial Securities Inc. “The global economy is recovering.
Starting with Nissan, companies are working hard at restoring
their operations.”  The Asia-Pacific gauge had its biggest weekly gain since
November last week as Japan moved to stabilize nuclear reactors
damaged by a March 11 earthquake and as companies from Cnooc Ltd.
to Bank of China Ltd.’s earnings surpassed estimates.  Japan’s Pre-Quake Recovery  Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average rose 2.6 percent after the
nation’s industrial production unexpectedly increased in
February, another sign that the economy was recovering before
the nation’s strongest earthquake this month shut factories and
caused power shortages.  Hitachi surged 8.7 percent to 437 yen in Tokyo. The company
will resume shipments of motors and turbines from April 3,
spokesman Tadashi Hisanaga said yesterday. Full production at
its main factory complex in Japan will re-start next month, the
Nikkei newspaper reported today, citing the plant’s general
manager Tatsuro Ishizuka.  Nissan Motor Co., Japan’s third-largest automaker by market
value, gained 3.8 percent to 731 yen after saying it expects
factories to return to normal by the end of June. IHI Corp., a
maker of heavy machinery, rose 6.4 percent to 200 yen after the
company resumed partial operations at its No. 1 and No. 2
factories in Soma, Fukushima prefecture, where it produces
aircraft parts and turbines.  Hong Kong’s  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  climbed 1.7 percent.  South
Korea ’s Kospi Index rose 0.9 percent.  Australia ’s S&P/ASX 200
Index advanced 1.4 percent.  New Zealand ’s NZX 50 Index increased
0.4 percent. China’s Shanghai Composite Index slipped 0.1
percent.  U.S. Economy  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index gained 0.4
percent today. The index rose 0.7 percent to a three-week high
yesterday in  New York  as Home Depot Inc. drove consumer
companies higher and energy shares rose amid speculation
production will increase in the Middle East.  U.S. employers added 190,000 jobs in March, according to
economist forecasts before the Labor Department’s April 1
payrolls report. The  unemployment rate  held at 8.9 percent in
March, economists said before the Labor Department reports the
figure. The jobless rate fell below 9 percent in February for
the first time in 22 months.  Li & Fung, which counts the U.S. as its biggest market,
climbed 5 percent to HK$39.95. Canon Inc., the world’s No.1
camera producer, gained 1.7 percent to 3,630 yen in Tokyo.  HTC
Corp. (2498) , the Taiwanese maker of mobile phones that gets about half
of sales from the U.S., rose 1.4 percent to NT$1,095 in Taipei.  PLDT Surges  Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. (TEL) , the nation’s
biggest phone company, surged 16 percent to 2,356 pesos, the
best performer on the MSCI Asia Pacific Index. PLDT, as the
company is also known, offered to buy rival Digital
Telecommunications Philippines Inc. in a deal valued at 74.1
billion pesos ($1.7 billion).  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index lost 3.4 percent this year to
yesterday, compared with gains of 4.9 percent by the  S&P 500  and
0.3 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the Asian
benchmark are valued at 13.4 times estimated earnings on average,
compared with 13.6 times for the S&P 500 and 11.1 times for the
Stoxx 600.  Cheung Kong, the developer controlled by billionaire Li Ka- shing, climbed 4 percent to HK$127.40 in Hong Kong. The company
said full-year net income rose 35 percent to HK$26.5 billion
($3.4 billion). That exceeded that average HK$20.2 billion
estimate of 12 analysts in a Bloomberg survey.  Hutch, Agricultural Bank  Hutchison Whampoa Ltd. (13) , the owner of ports and phone
companies that’s also controlled by Li, jumped 5.1 percent to
HK$93.35. The company said annual net income climbed 47 percent
to HK$20 billion. That beat that HK$16.4 billion average of nine
analysts’ estimates compiled by Bloomberg.  Agricultural Bank of China advanced 2.7 percent to HK$4.24.
The lender said full-year net income increased 46 percent to
94.87 billion yuan ($14.5 billion) from a year ago. That
surpassed the 91.1 billion yuan average estimate of 17 analysts
compiled by Bloomberg.  A gauge of raw-material producers posted the biggest
advance among the 10 industry groups in the MSCI Asia Pacific.
All but one of the sub-indexes advanced.  Jiangxi Copper Co., China’s largest producer of the metal,
rose 5.5 percent to HK$26 in Hong Kong. The company posted a 158
percent increase in second-half profit because of rising copper
demand and higher prices.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) , the world’s biggest mining company,
increased 2 percent to A$45.61 in Sydney. Rival Rio Tinto Group
advanced 2.4 percent to A$84.28. Cnooc Ltd., China’s biggest
offshore energy producer, climbed 2.3 percent to HK$19.46 in
Hong Kong.  The London Metal Exchange Index of prices for six
industrial metals including copper and aluminum gained 0.9
percent yesterday. Crude oil for May delivery increased 0.8
percent to $104.79 a barrel in New York, rising for the first
time in four days.  To contact the reporters on this story:
